{{Year nav topic5|1895|film}} {{Yearsinfilm}}
The following is an overview of the events of '''1895 in film''', including a list of films released and notable births.
==Events== * February–March – [[Robert W. Paul]] and [[Birt Acres]] build and run the first working [[35 mm]] movie [[camera]] in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], the Kineopticon. Their first films include ''[[Incident at Clovelly Cottage]]'', ''[[The Oxford and Cambridge University Boat Race (1895 film)|The Oxford and Cambridge University Boat Race]]'' and ''[[Rough Sea at Dover]]''.<ref name=HDC>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Burns|work=The History of the Discovery of Cinematography|title=Chapter 15, 1895–1900|url=http://www.precinemahistory.net/1895.htm|year=1999|accessdate=2011-08-14| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724021600/http://www.precinemahistory.net/1895.htm| archivedate= 24 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl=no}}</ref> * In France, the brothers [[Auguste Lumière|Auguste]] and [[Louis Lumière]], design and built a lightweight, hand-held motion picture camera called the [[Cinématographe]]. They discover that their machine can also be used to project images onto a large screen. The Lumière brothers create several short films at this time that are considered to be pivotal in the history of motion pictures.<ref name=HDC/> * February 13 – [[Auguste and Louis Lumière]] patent the ''Cinematographe'', a combination [[movie camera]] and [[Movie projector|projector]]. * March 22 – First display of [[film|motion pictures]] by [[Auguste and Louis Lumière]] (private screening). * May 27 – Birt Acres [[patent]]s the Kineopticon under his own name. * Late September – [[C. Francis Jenkins]] and [[Thomas Armat]] demonstrate their [[Phantoscope]], a motion picture projector, in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] at the [[Cotton States and International Exposition (1895)|Cotton States and International Exposition]]. *November – In Germany, Emil and [[Max Skladanowsky]] develop their own film projector. * December 28 – The [[Auguste and Louis Lumière|Lumière brothers]] have their first paying audience at the Grand Café ''Boulevard des Capucines'' in Paris — this date is sometimes considered the debut of the motion picture as an entertainment medium. * December 30 – The [[American Mutoscope and Biograph Company]] motion pictures is founded in New Jersey by the KMCD Syndicate of [[William Kennedy Dickson]], Henry Marvin, [[Herman Casler]] and [[Elias Koopman]].<ref name=Photoplay>{{cite news|work=[[Photoplay]]|author=[[Terry Ramsaye]]|date=January 1925|page=121|title=The Romantic History of the Motion Picture|url=https://archive.org/stream/pho28chic#page/n124/mode/1up|accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref> *[[Annabelle Moore|Annabelle]] the Dancer is a sensation in shorts such as [[Annabelle Serpentine Dance]] *[[William Kennedy Dickson]] and his sister Antonia publish ''[[History of the Kinetograph, Kinetoscope, and Kinetophonograph]]'' in the United States with a preface by [[Thomas Edison]], the first history of the subject. *[[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont Pictures]] founded by the engineer-turned-inventor, [[Léon Gaumont]]. [[Woodville Latham]] and his sons develop the Latham Loop – the concept of loose loops of film on either side of the [[intermittent movement]] to prevent stress from the jerky movement. This is debuted in the [[Eidoloscope]], which is also the first widescreen format (1.85:1). * [[Herman Casler]] of American Mutoscope Company, a.k.a. [[American Mutoscope and Biograph Company]] manufactures the Biograph 68&nbsp;mm camera, which will become the first successful large format 68mm (70mm) film. * [[Henri Joly]] debuts his Joly-Normandin 60&nbsp;mm format.
==Films released in 1895== [[File:L'ArroseurArrosé.jpg|thumb|250px|''L'Arroseur arrosé'' (1895) the earliest known instance of film [[comedy]], as well as the first use of film to portray a [[fiction]]al story.]] *''[[Akrobatisches Potpourri]]'' *''[[Annabelle Serpentine Dance]]'', directed by [[William Heise]], starring [[Annabelle Moore]] *''[[L'Arrivée d'un Train en Gare de la Ciotat|Arrival of a Train at La Ciotat]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''[[Repas de bébé|The Baby's Meal]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]], starring [[Auguste Lumiere]], (his wife) Marguerite, and (their daughter) Andrée *''[[Bauerntanz zweier Kinder]]'' *''Billy Edwards and the Unknown a.k.a. Billy Edwards Boxing'' *''[[Les Forgerons|The Blacksmiths]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''[[Barque sortant du port|Boat Leaving The Port]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''[[Boxing Kangaroo (film)|Boxing Kangaroo]]'' *''[[Partie de cartes|Card Party]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''[[La Charcuterie mécanique]] *''[[Démolition d'un mur|Demolition Of A Wall]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] and starring [[Auguste Lumiere]], the man in charge...pointing *''[[The Derby (1895 film)|The Derby]]'', directed by [[Birt Acres]] *''[[The Dickson Experimental Sound Film]]'', directed by and starring [[William K. L. Dickson]] on violin. First sound film. *''[[The Execution of Mary Stuart]]'', directed by [[Alfred Clark (director)|Alfred Clark]]. First special effect (stop camera edit effect) in cinema. *''[[Incident at Clovelly Cottage]]'', shot by [[Birt Acres]] *''[[La Pêche aux poissons rouges|Fishing For Goldfish]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]], starring [[Auguste Lumiere]] and (his daughter) Andrée *''[[Opening of the Kiel Canal]]'' *''[[The Oxford and Cambridge University Boat Race (1895 film)|The Oxford and Cambridge University Boat Race]]'' *''[[Place des Cordeliers à Lyon|Cordeliers' Square in Lyons]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''Photograph'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''[[The Photographical Congress Arrives in Lyon]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''Princess Ali a.k.a. Egyptian Dance'' *''[[Rough Sea at Dover]]'', directed by [[Birt Acres]] *''[[Le Saut à la couverture]]'' *''[[Serpentinen Tanz]]'' *''[[L'Arroseur Arrosé|The Sprinkler Sprinkled]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]]. May be the first outdoor comedy film ever made. *''[[La Mer (film)|Swimming In The Sea]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''Transformation By Hats, Comic View'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]] *''[[La Voltige]]'' *''Das Wintergartenprogramm'', directed by [[Max Skladanowsky]] *''[[Workers Leaving the Lumière Factory]]'', directed by [[Louis Lumiere]]
==Births== *February 7 – [[Anita Stewart]], American actress and producer (died [[1961 in film|1961]]) *February 25 – [[Einar Axelsson]], Swedish actor (died [[1971 in film|1971]]) *March 11 – [[Shemp Howard]], American actor (died [[1955 in film|1955]]) *March 25 – [[Valéry Inkijinoff]], French actor of Russian-Buryat origin (died [[1973 in film|1973]]) *March 27 – [[Betty Schade]], German-born American actress (died [[1982 in film|1982]]) *April 7 – [[Margarete Schön]], German actress (died [[1985 in film|1985]]) *May 6 – [[Rudolph Valentino]], Italian actor (died [[1926 in film|1926]]) *June 10 – [[Hattie McDaniel]], American actress (died [[1952 in film|1952]]) *July 25 – [[Ingeborg Spangsfeldt]], Danish actress (died [[1968 in film|1968]]) *July 26 – [[Gracie Allen]], American actress (died [[1964 in film|1964]]) *September 11 – [[Uno Henning]], Swedish actor (died [[1970 in film|1970]]) *September 22 – [[Paul Muni]], Austrian-born American stage and film actor (died [[1967 in film|1967]]) *October 4 – [[Buster Keaton]], American actor and director (died [[1966 in film|1966]]) *October 21 – [[Edna Purviance]], American actress (died [[1958 in film|1958]]) *November 14 – [[Louise Huff]], American actress (died [[1973 in film|1973]]) *December 3 – [[Tadeusz Olsza]], Polish actor (died [[1975 in film|1975]])
