{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
[[Image:ZiguinchorImpluviumEntrance.jpg|thumb|The 'case à impluvium' in Ziguinchor, Casamance, Senegal, a centre for the arts run by the Alliance Franco-Sénégalaise]]
An '''impluvium''' is a type of dwelling typical of the [[Jola people|Jola]] in the [[Casamance]] region of [[Senegal]]. It is a circular mud building, built with a ring of rooms around a walkway that circumscribes a central water trench, fed by an opening that allows water into the building. Impluvia remain cool in very hot weather as the water evaporates. There is a particularly fine example that serves as a hotel in [[Enampore]]. Impluvial architecture is also used by the [[Igbo people|Igbo]], [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] and [[Edo]] of southern Nigeria, in which they consist of small courtyards cornered with large pots to collect rain water. Edo and Yoruba houses usually consist of several impluvia and courts. The amount and size of these courts depend on the social and economic status of the individual. Royal palaces in Yorubaland and the [[Kingdom of Benin]] possessed hundreds of impluvia sometimes floored with elaborate pavements made of potsherds and quartz pebbles arranged in decorative patterns.

==History==
The structures came into existence due to the areas climate and environment of been a rain forest. the region receives a lot of precipitation during the rain season and losses the water due to the soils polarity and so the people came up with a way to store the water for the dry season and they came up with the impluvial.

